---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { APPS, SEGMENTS, USE_CASES, allPaths, appBySlug, appPairs, description, pageTitle, siteFromHost } from '../content';
const site = siteFromHost();
const slug = Astro.params.slug || '';
const path = Array.isArray(slug) ? slug.join('/') : slug;
const parts = path.split('/').filter(Boolean);
const title = pageTitle(site, path);
const desc = description(site, path);
function channelApps(){ return APPS.filter(a => a.channels.includes(site.channel) || a.channels.includes('marketing')); }
let valid = allPaths().includes(path);
if (!valid) return Astro.redirect('/');
const pairs = appPairs();
const primaryApps = channelApps().slice(0,12);
const catalogPrinciple = `A Shopify email tool should be judged by everyday usefulness. Can the team create a clean segment quickly, write a product-aware message without fighting the editor, exclude customers who should not receive the offer, and understand whether the send helped the business? Broad email tooling is not only about advanced automation; it is about reducing the small frictions that stop merchants from communicating consistently.`;
const implementationPrinciple = `The best implementation starts with a small library of dependable jobs: subscribe and welcome, announce and launch, recover and reassure, educate and support, replenish and cross-sell, win back and suppress. Each job needs different data, copy, timing, and reporting. A tool that is excellent for weekly campaigns but weak for lifecycle automation may still be right for an early store; a larger brand may need deeper governance and experimentation.`;
const riskPrinciple = `Be careful with tools that look simple only because they hide important controls. Shopify email work eventually needs consent handling, suppression logic, product and order filters, deliverability hygiene, reusable content modules, and cost modeling as the customer list grows. If a system cannot support those basics, the store will either send less than it should or send too broadly and damage trust.`;
const routeManual = `For this specific page, judge the tool through the actual Shopify workflow implied by the title rather than through a generic software checklist. The right answer depends on who owns email, how often the store sends, how much of the catalog changes every month, whether campaigns need product blocks or editorial content, and how cleanly the system handles customers who should be excluded. A small merchant may value speed and clarity over depth. A scaling brand may need governance, testing, customer-stage rules, and reporting that separates campaign lift from revenue that would have happened anyway.`;
const contentDepth = `A useful page should leave the merchant with an operating decision. Before buying, write down the next four sends or flows the team needs to launch. Name the audience, the Shopify data required, the message angle, the suppression rules, the owner, and the metric that will decide whether the work stays live. Then open the tool and see whether those decisions feel natural. If the tool hides these steps, it is probably too shallow for a serious retention program. If it makes them easier, it belongs on the shortlist even when a larger competitor has more features.`;
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={desc} site={site} path={`/${path}`}>
  <section class="bg-[#111827] py-16 text-white"><div class="container"><span class="badge badge-dark">Shopify email tools catalog</span><h1 class="hero-title mt-5 text-white">{title}</h1><p class="mt-6 max-w-4xl text-xl text-indigo-100">{desc} This page focuses on practical email tooling: campaign workflow, customer data, automations, templates, reporting, and the fit between a Shopify team's workload and the software it can operate.</p></div></section>

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="mb-8 max-w-3xl"><h2 class="text-4xl font-black">All Shopify email tools in the catalog</h2><p class="mt-4 text-slate-600">Start here when you want a broad scan of apps that can handle newsletters, automated email, lifecycle messages, customer education, or retention workflows for Shopify.</p></div><div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-4">{APPS.map((app,i)=><a class="card" href={`/apps/${app.slug}`}><div class="text-xs font-black uppercase tracking-wide text-indigo-700">Tool {i+1}</div><h2 class="mt-3 text-2xl font-black text-slate-950">{app.name}</h2><p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-600">Best for {app.bestFor}.</p><p class="mt-4 text-sm font-bold">{app.pricing}</p></a>)}</div></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container grid gap-8 py-14 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_320px]"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>{app.name} as a Shopify email tool</h2><p>{app.shopifyFit} For the keyword <strong>{site.primaryKeyword}</strong>, the buying question is intentionally broad: can {app.name} help the store communicate more clearly with subscribers and customers across campaigns, automations, and service-like moments?</p><p>{catalogPrinciple}</p><h2>Where it fits</h2><p>{app.name} is strongest for {app.bestFor}. A merchant should consider it when the next stage of growth requires better email execution, not merely more email volume. Good fit means the tool supports the current team's capacity and leaves room for more sophisticated segmentation later.</p><p>{implementationPrinciple}</p><h2>Strengths</h2><ul>{app.strengths.map(s=><li>{s}</li>)}</ul><h2>Limits to watch</h2><ul>{app.limits.map(l=><li>{l}</li>)}</ul><p>{riskPrinciple}</p><h2>Buying advice</h2><p>Ask the team to build one campaign, one welcome flow, one post-purchase message, and one reactivation segment before judging the interface. If the work feels clear and reporting explains what happened, {app.name} may be a strong fit. If simple jobs require workarounds, choose another email tool before the customer file grows larger.</p></article><aside class="card h-fit"><div class="text-sm font-black text-indigo-700">Snapshot</div><dl class="mt-4 space-y-3 text-sm"><div><dt class="font-black">Category</dt><dd>{app.category}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black">Pricing</dt><dd>{app.pricing}</dd></div><div><dt class="font-black">Best for</dt><dd>{app.bestFor}</dd></div></dl><a class="btn btn-primary mt-6 w-full" href="https://sequenzy.com">Compare with Sequenzy</a></aside></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3">{pairs.map(([a,b])=><a class="card" href={`/compare/${a.slug}-vs-${b.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{a.name} vs {b.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Which email tool better fits a Shopify workflow?</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container py-14"><div class="card overflow-x-auto"><table class="data-table"><thead><tr><th>Criteria</th><th>{a?.name}</th><th>{b?.name}</th><th>Catalog takeaway</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Best fit</td><td>{a?.bestFor}</td><td>{b?.bestFor}</td><td>Choose the tool that matches the email jobs your team can actually maintain.</td></tr><tr><td>Pricing</td><td>{a?.pricing}</td><td>{b?.pricing}</td><td>Compare cost against contacts, send volume, feature gates, and implementation time.</td></tr><tr><td>Strength</td><td>{a?.strengths[0]}</td><td>{b?.strengths[0]}</td><td>Do not pay for sophistication the team will not use.</td></tr></tbody></table></div><article class="prose-shopify mt-8 card"><h2>Verdict for {site.primaryKeyword}</h2><p>{a?.name} is stronger when the merchant needs {a?.bestFor}. {b?.name} is stronger when the merchant needs {b?.bestFor}. The right answer depends on whether the store's next bottleneck is campaign speed, automation depth, segmentation, reporting, deliverability, or the ability to coordinate email with other lifecycle channels.</p><p>{catalogPrinciple}</p><p>{implementationPrinciple}</p><p>{riskPrinciple}</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{SEGMENTS.map(s=><a class="card" href={`/for/${s.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{s.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Email tooling problem: {s.pain}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Email tool selection for {seg.name}</h2><p>{seg.name} have to plan around {seg.pain}. That means the email tool should support the messages customers expect from this category, not a generic newsletter rhythm borrowed from another store.</p><p>{catalogPrinciple}</p><h2>Recommended shortlist</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><p>{implementationPrinciple}</p><p>{riskPrinciple}</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && !parts[1] && <section class="container py-14"><div class="grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-3">{USE_CASES.map(u=><a class="card" href={`/use-cases/${u.slug}`}><h2 class="text-xl font-black">{u.name}</h2><p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-600">Use email tools to {u.job}.</p></a>)}</div></section>}
  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best Shopify email tools for {u.name}</h2><p>The job of {u.name} is to {u.job}. The email tool should make that job repeatable with Shopify data, clear copy, controlled targeting, and reporting that distinguishes useful communication from extra noise.</p><p>{catalogPrinciple}</p><h2>Apps to consider</h2><ul>{primaryApps.slice(0,8).map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a>: {a.shopifyFit}</li>)}</ul><p>{implementationPrinciple}</p><p>{riskPrinciple}</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'alternatives' && (() => { const app=appBySlug((parts[1]||'').replace('-alternative',''))!; const alts=APPS.filter(a=>a.slug!==app.slug).slice(0,8); return <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Best {app.name} alternatives for Shopify email</h2><p>Merchants compare {app.name} alternatives when the current tool no longer matches campaign workflow, automation needs, cost expectations, segmentation depth, or reporting requirements.</p><p>{catalogPrinciple}</p><h2>Alternatives to review</h2><ul>{alts.map(a=><li><a class="link" href={`/apps/${a.slug}`}>{a.name}</a> — {a.bestFor}</li>)}</ul><p>{implementationPrinciple}</p><p>{riskPrinciple}</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'guides' && <section class="container py-14"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Shopify email tools buying framework</h2><p>Choose {site.primaryKeyword} by naming the work first. Some merchants need a low-friction campaign sender; others need lifecycle automation, replenishment messages, launch coordination, suppression controls, or reporting that connects email activity to repeat revenue.</p><p>{catalogPrinciple}</p><p>{implementationPrinciple}</p><p>{riskPrinciple}</p><h2>Useful starting pages</h2><ul><li><a class="link" href="/apps">All tools</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/compare">Comparisons</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/use-cases/welcome-series">Welcome series guide</a></li><li><a class="link" href="/for/beauty">Beauty store guide</a></li></ul></article></section>}

  {parts[0] === 'apps' && parts[1] && (() => { const app = appBySlug(parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Implementation example for {app.name}</h2><p>Test {app.name} with a concrete Shopify workload rather than a tour of menus. Build a product launch campaign for a known segment, a welcome sequence for new subscribers, a post-purchase education email for a recent order, and a winback segment for customers who bought once but have not returned. This sample gives the team four different pressures: campaign speed, event handling, customer-stage logic, and reporting.</p><p>For the launch campaign, choose one collection, exclude recent buyers of the promoted product, add a product block with live pricing, and create two audience variants: high-intent customers who viewed or bought related products and a broader subscriber group that needs more education. For the welcome sequence, confirm the app can separate subscribers who have never purchased from customers who subscribed after checkout. For the post-purchase message, make sure order contents drive the copy. For winback, require suppression for customers currently in replenishment, support, or VIP flows.</p><h2>Scoring rubric</h2><ul><li><strong>Data access:</strong> does {app.name} read Shopify orders, products, customer tags, checkout events, consent, discounts, and product categories without manual exports?</li><li><strong>Operating speed:</strong> can a marketer build and QA the four test messages without developer help or side spreadsheets?</li><li><strong>Control:</strong> are delays, exclusions, entry rules, exits, naming, approvals, and preview data clear enough for a busy week?</li><li><strong>Measurement:</strong> can reporting explain revenue by audience, customer stage, discount use, campaign, and flow rather than only total attributed sales?</li><li><strong>Cost fit:</strong> does pricing still make sense when subscribers, customer profiles, send volume, and add-ons grow?</li></ul><p>A high score does not mean the app has every enterprise feature. It means the merchant can run the next layer of email without creating operational debt.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'compare' && parts[1] && (() => { const [a,b] = parts[1].split('-vs-').map(appBySlug); return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>How to run a fair {a?.name} vs {b?.name} trial</h2><p>Do not compare {a?.name} and {b?.name} by reading feature checklists in isolation. Rebuild the same Shopify email workload in both tools: one newsletter, one welcome series, one abandoned checkout or browse-abandon flow, one post-purchase education message, and one customer reactivation segment. Use the same products, audiences, exclusions, copy outline, and metrics. The better tool is the one that makes the desired customer experience easier to create, explain, approve, and improve.</p><p>Give each platform the same scoring sheet. Award points for product data access, segment clarity, flow editing, template reuse, QA and preview quality, reporting depth, cost predictability, deliverability controls, and ease of migration. Then write a short operational note for each score. For example: “segment built in ten minutes, but exclusion logic was hard to audit” is more useful than “segmentation is good.”</p><h2>Migration risks in this comparison</h2><p>If a store switches between these tools, the risky work is not only moving templates. Forms, popups, consent records, DNS, sending domains, flows, coupon logic, customer tags, UTM conventions, attribution windows, product feeds, historical segments, and suppression lists all need owners. Run both platforms in parallel only long enough to verify data and avoid duplicate sends. Freeze major campaigns during cutover week, export critical templates and segment definitions, and send internal test orders through every key flow before turning the old system off.</p><h2>Decision rule</h2><p>Choose {a?.name} if its strengths match the most expensive bottleneck in the store's email program. Choose {b?.name} if it handles that bottleneck with less friction or better economics. If both can run the same flows, the tie-breakers are usually team comfort, reporting clarity, migration risk, and whether the next six months require more campaign speed or more lifecycle depth.</p></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'use-cases' && parts[1] && (() => { const u=USE_CASES.find(x=>x.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Workflow blueprint for {u.name}</h2><p>Turn {u.name} into a written operating spec before choosing software. The spec should name the trigger, audience, excluded customers, message promise, product logic, timing, owner, and success metric. For this use case, the job is to {u.job}; the email tool should make that job easier with Shopify data instead of forcing the team to approximate behavior with broad lists.</p><h2>Example setup</h2><p>Start with a narrow audience that clearly matches the use case. Add exclusions for recent buyers, customers in conflicting flows, subscribers with no engagement, customers who used a code that changes the offer, and any account type that needs separate treatment. Write the first message around the customer's problem, not around the app's automation feature. Add product blocks only when they clarify the next action. Use a delay that matches buying behavior, then add follow-up only if it answers a new objection.</p><h2>Measurement plan</h2><p>Track more than opens and attributed revenue. Watch revenue per recipient, placed order rate, unsubscribe rate, complaint rate, discount use, repeat purchase, time to second order, and replies that reveal confusion. If the use case is educational, lower support tickets and better product adoption may matter as much as immediate sales. If it is promotional, contribution margin and list fatigue matter more than top-line revenue.</p><h2>Mistakes to avoid</h2><ul><li>Sending to everyone because the segment is easy to build.</li><li>Adding a discount before testing clarity, proof, timing, or product education.</li><li>Letting the flow run forever without reviewing exclusions and exits.</li><li>Judging the use case only by revenue that the platform attributes to the email.</li></ul></article></section> })()}

  {parts[0] === 'for' && parts[1] && (() => { const seg=SEGMENTS.find(s=>s.slug===parts[1])!; return <section class="container pb-12"><article class="prose-shopify card"><h2>Category-specific email plan for {seg.name}</h2><p>{seg.name} need email tooling that respects {seg.pain}. Start by listing the five messages customers actually need from this category: a first-purchase confidence builder, a product education message, a reorder or cross-sell moment, a promotional announcement, and a reactivation path. The right app should support those jobs without forcing the brand into a generic newsletter calendar.</p><p>Segmentation should reflect category behavior. For this store type, useful segments may include first-time shoppers, repeat buyers, product-category buyers, high-value customers, subscribers who have not purchased, discount-sensitive customers, and customers near a natural reorder or gift window. Suppression is just as important: exclude recent buyers from broad promos, prevent conflicting flows, and treat support cases or wholesale accounts carefully.</p><p>When comparing apps, ask which one makes the category's real constraints easier to operate. If the app cannot use the data that explains {seg.pain}, the store will end up sending broad campaigns that look active but do not improve customer experience.</p></article></section> })()}

  <section class="bg-white py-14">
    <div class="container">
      <article class="prose-shopify card">
        <h2>Deeper operating framework for {title}</h2>
        <p>Use this page as a decision worksheet. A shallow email tools page names apps; a useful one explains the work a merchant must complete after installing the app. For Shopify, that work normally includes collecting consent, building dependable segments, writing product-aware messages, suppressing customers who should not receive an offer, measuring revenue quality, and keeping the workflow simple enough to repeat during launches, holidays, and inventory changes.</p>
        <h3>Examples to build during a trial</h3>
        <p>Build a campaign for a new product, a campaign for an existing best seller, a flow for a new subscriber, a flow for a recent buyer, and a segment for a lapsed customer. These examples expose different weaknesses. Product launches test inventory and collection data. Best-seller campaigns test exclusion logic and fatigue management. Welcome flows test consent and first-purchase timing. Post-purchase messages test order data and education. Lapsed-customer segments test lifecycle reporting and winback economics.</p>
        <h3>Rubric for scoring the page topic</h3>
        <p>Score every contender on data depth, day-to-day speed, automation control, segmentation clarity, deliverability safeguards, analytics, migration effort, and price at future list size. A score of five means the team can complete the work with native controls and clear reporting. A score of three means the work is possible but requires conventions, manual checks, or agency help. A score of one means the app technically sends email but does not support the Shopify decision this page is about.</p>
        <h3>Implementation steps</h3>
        <p>First, document current forms, flows, segments, templates, coupon codes, DNS records, sending domains, suppression lists, and analytics tags. Second, rebuild only the essential journeys before migrating every historical idea. Third, run internal test orders that cover first purchase, repeat purchase, discounted order, high-value order, out-of-stock item, and unsubscribe. Fourth, launch to a small segment and watch unsubscribes, complaints, and unexpected exclusions before widening the audience.</p>
        <h3>Migration risks</h3>
        <p>The most common migration failures are invisible until revenue drops: a popup stops collecting consent, a welcome flow double-sends, old tags no longer map to new segments, discount codes leak, abandoned checkout messages continue after purchase, or attribution changes make performance look better or worse than it is. Assign an owner to each risk. Keep screenshots of old logic, export templates, save segment definitions in plain language, and avoid major promotional sends during the switch.</p>
        <h3>Measurement that matters</h3>
        <p>Measure opens and clicks only as diagnostic signals. Business decisions should use revenue per recipient, placed order rate, contribution margin, discount dependency, repeat purchase, unsubscribe rate, spam complaints, deliverability, customer replies, and incremental lift where possible. For automated flows, review both immediate conversion and downstream behavior. An email that earns a quick sale but increases refunds, support tickets, or future unsubscribes may not be a win.</p>
        <h3>Final advice</h3>
        <p>The right Shopify email tool is the one the team can operate with discipline. It should make better customer communication easier: clearer segments, cleaner timing, useful personalization, safer exclusions, and reporting that teaches the next improvement. If a tool requires constant workarounds during the trial, those workarounds will multiply after the store adds more products, more subscribers, more flows, and more campaigns.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="container pb-16">
    <article class="prose-shopify card border-indigo-200 bg-indigo-50/70">
      <h2>Decision notes for this Shopify email tools page</h2>
      <p>{routeManual}</p>
      <p>{contentDepth}</p>
      <h3>What to test before choosing</h3>
      <p>Build a short trial around work, not around feature discovery. Create one campaign to a product-aware segment, one automated message that reacts to customer behavior, one suppression rule that protects recent buyers or low-intent subscribers, and one report that explains whether the send was worth repeating. The strongest tool is the one that lets the team complete those jobs without inventing side spreadsheets, manual exports, or fragile naming conventions.</p>
      <h3>How to avoid overbuying</h3>
      <p>Do not buy the largest email platform simply because it can do everything. Shopify teams usually fail because the weekly email workflow is unclear, not because the app lacks an obscure enterprise feature. If the page is about comparisons, focus on the tradeoff that affects tomorrow's work. If it is about a use case, focus on timing, audience, copy, and measurement. If it is about a store type, focus on the category-specific customer behavior that makes generic email advice weak.</p>
      <h3>Final selection checklist</h3>
      <p>Before making the decision, ask five concrete questions. Can the tool read the Shopify data this page depends on without manual exports? Can a marketer update the message, segment, and product block without developer help? Can the team suppress recent buyers, unengaged subscribers, and customers in conflicting flows? Can reporting show revenue quality rather than only total attributed sales? Can the workflow still make sense during a busy launch, holiday promotion, or inventory change? If the answer is no, the tool may still be useful, but it should not be treated as the main operating layer for Shopify email.</p>
      <p>The safest shortlist is usually one practical operator-first option, one deep ecommerce database option, and one lighter campaign tool. Compare them by rebuilding the same workflow in each product. The winner should make the desired customer experience easier to create, easier to explain, and easier to improve next month.</p>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
